
[1]chaplain

   CHAPLAIN, n.

   1. An ecclesiastic who has a chapel, or who performs service in a
   chapel. The king of Great Britain has forty-eight chaplains, who
   attend, four each month, to perform divine service for the royal
   family. Princes also, and persons of quality have chaplains, who
   officiate in their chapels.

   2. A clergyman who belongs to a ship of war, or to a regiment of land
   forces, for performing divine service.

   3. A clergyman who is retained to perform divine service in a family.

   Chaplains of the Pope, are auditors or judges of causes in the sacred
   palace.
